  "text": "Four sets of 90 to 100 simulations used to produce bifurcation diagrams (high precision, low precision, and each with errors; see below) then served as a database describing error responses of the model. This communication focuses on the details of the model's recovery after an error and the effects of presynaptic spike timing precision on that recovery, and so a few illustrative behaviors were selected. The behaviors chosen are archetypical of the full range of dynamical behavior types exhibited by driven nonlinear oscillators: 1:1 locking (period 1), 1:2 locking (period 2), 2:3 locking (period 3, the longest periodic behavior for this model with significant extent along the N/I scale), two quasiperiodicities (low-N/I < 1.0-and high-N/I > 1.0-rate), and chaos. An additional behavior was chosen to illustrate the effects of proximity to a bifurcation. A more complete examination of the global behavior of error correction (e.g., two-and three-dimensional bifurcation structure) is under way [CITATION_1] .",
